# ${project_name} — TaskOps Reference

> Prefix: ${prefix} | DB: taskops.db | Created: ${timestamp}

⚠️ **TaskOps manages only `taskops.db` and this file. It does NOT modify any other project files.**

---

## When to Update TaskOps

| Event | Commands |
|-------|----------|
| New TODO list to track | `workflow create` → `workflow import` |
| Start working on a task | `task update <ID> --status in_progress` + `op start <ID>` |
| Complete a task | `task update <ID> --status done` + `op complete <ID>` |
| Plan changes (full replace) | `workflow import <W-ID> --structure '<json>'` |
| Minor plan tweak | `plan update --changes '<json>'` |
| Check current state | `query show` or `query status` |

---

## TODO → ETS Conversion Guide

Your existing TODO list maps to TaskOps structure as follows:

| TODO element | TaskOps element |
|-------------|----------------|
| Section header (`## Phase 1`) | Epic |
| Checkbox item (`- [ ] Do X`) | Task |
| Nested checkbox | SubTask (Task with Task parent) |

One TODO list = one Workflow (`${prefix}-W001`, `${prefix}-W002`, ...).

**To import a TODO list:**

1. Convert your TODO list to this JSON format:
```json
{
  "epics": [
    {
      "title": "Phase 1: Setup",
      "tasks": [
        {
          "title": "Task title",
          "description": "optional detail",
          "subtasks": [{"title": "SubTask title"}]
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

2. Create a workflow and import:
```bash
python -m cli --db taskops.db workflow create --title "My Plan"
python -m cli --db taskops.db workflow import ${prefix}-W001 --structure '<json>'
```

3. Verify the result:
```bash
python -m cli --db taskops.db query show
```

